				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E=0$$\end{document} or ϵ=μ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\epsilon =\mu $$\end{document} characterizes the fundamental Fermi energy level of the system which is assumed to be constant. Hence, current model is most appropriate for metals and nano-metallic density regime and beyond. Figure 1d, on the other hand, shows the variation plasmon temperature, Tp\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
